momentary fulfillment of desire in the happy ending to the pleasurable torment of an indeterminate ending. The contributors also consider how film endings open onto larger questions relating to endings in our time. They suggest how a film ending's hidden counternarrative can be read as a political act, how our interpretation of a film ending parallels the end of a psychoanalytical session, how film endings reveal our anxieties and fears, and how cinema itself might end with the increasing intervention of digital technologies that reorient the spectator's sense of temporality and closure. Films by Akira Kurosawa, Lars von Trier, Joon-Hwan Jang, Claire Denis, Christopher Nolan, Jane Campion, John Huston, and Spike Jonze, among others, are discussed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aMotion picturesxEditing. 0aMotion picturesxPhilosophy. 0aMotion picturesxPsychological aspects. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Film Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Feminist. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aPsychology : Psychoanalysis. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh1 aButler, Rex, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDenny, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEngley, Ryan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedlander, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJagodzinski, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKordela, A. Kiarina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrips, Henry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKunkle, Sheila, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKunkle, Sheila, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/